ingredients.Name: chicken thighs, deboned with skin on

directions.Direction: For the Pasta:
1. On a clean surface, pile 3/4 cup of flour and shape it into a well.
2. Add 6 egg yolks and a pinch of salt to the well.
3. Beat the yolks with a fork, gradually incorporating the flour until a thick paste forms.
4. Combine with the remaining flour until a dough ball forms, adjusting with extra flour or water as needed.
5. Knead the dough until smooth and elastic. Cover with plastic wrap and let it rest for 30 minutes.
6. Divide the dough in half and roll each half into a thin rectangular sheet.
7. Fold the dough like an accordion and slice it into 1 cm strips. Unravel into tagliatelle, coat in flour, form into nests, and set aside.
For the Chicken:
1. Debone 2 chicken thighs, keeping the skin on, and trim any excess skin. Season both sides with salt.
2. Place the chicken thighs in a cold pan, skin side down, with 3 tbsp olive oil. Heat the pan to medium, applying light pressure to ensure full contact with the pan.
3. Sear the chicken until the skin is golden and crispy, then flip the thighs and raise the heat to medium-high.

4. Add 4 tbsp butter, 1 bunch of thyme, and 2 smashed garlic cloves. Baste the chicken until the internal temperature reaches 160°F. Transfer to a wire rack, pour the basting butter over, and keep warm in a 150°F oven.
For the Sauce:
1. Drain the excess butter and oil from the chicken pan. Add 2 tbsp butter to the pan and heat over medium.
2. Add 2/3 cup finely diced onion with a pinch of salt and sauté until softened.
3. Add 2 sliced garlic cloves and stir until fragrant.
4. Deglaze the pan with 1.5 cups dry white wine, scraping up any browned bits. Reduce the wine until the liquid evaporates.
5. Pour in 1.5 cups heavy cream and bring to a light simmer.
6. Stir in 1 cup grated Parmigiano Reggiano and black pepper, adjusting salt if needed.
To Serve:
1. Bring a pot of heavily salted water to a boil. Cook the pasta until it floats, about 1-2 minutes.
2. Transfer the pasta directly to the sauce, adding 1/2 cup pasta water. Stir over medium heat until well combined.
3. Plate the pasta, top with sliced chicken thigh, and garnish with extra Parmigiano Reggiano and chopped parsley.

directions.Direction: For the Duck Ragu:
Begin by salting the duck leg quarters. Place them skin side down in a cold saucepan. Set over medium heat and render the fat until the skin is crispy. Remove the duck legs and drain excess fat.
Add brunoise celery, carrot, and onion to the saucepan. Season with a pinch of salt and sauté until translucent.
Add sliced garlic and sauté for 30 seconds. Stir in tomato paste until fond develops on the bottom of the pan.
Deglaze the pan with red wine, scraping up any browned bits. Add crushed tomatoes and chicken stock.
Return the duck legs to the pan, cover loosely, and bring to a light simmer. Transfer to a preheated oven at 325°F (160°C) for 2 hours or until very tender.
Remove from the oven, separate the duck meat from the bones, and shred the meat. Place shredded meat in a pot and ladle over enough sauce to cover. Reserve any leftover sauce.
Bring the pot to a light simmer, then stir in heavy whipping cream. Salt to taste.
For the Gnocchi:
Preheat oven to 400°F (200°C). Coat Yukon gold potatoes in olive oil and bake for 1 hour until tender. Let cool slightly, then slice in half and scoop out the insides.

Pass the potato through a potato ricer onto a cutting board, forming a large pile. Add egg yolks, salt, and start with 2/3 cup of flour. Fold in flour until combined, adding more as needed until the dough forms a cohesive mass. Do not overwork.

On a floured surface, roll the dough into a log. Cut into small sections and shape into gnocchi by rolling into small rods, then cutting into 1-inch pieces and pinching the sides to form pillow shapes. Place on a generously floured baking sheet.
To Finish the Dish:

In a pan, melt butter over medium-high heat. Cook gnocchi in salted boiling water until they float to the top, about 1-2 minutes. Remove with a slotted spoon and add cooked gnocchi to the butter, searing on both sides until crispy.
Once crispy, add a couple spoonfuls of duck ragu sauce to lightly coat each gnocchi. Add a small ladle of pasta water, then grate in a generous amount of Parmigiano Reggiano. Toss to combine.
Plate the gnocchi on a hot dish, topped with additional Parmigiano Reggiano. Serve and enjoy immediately.

directions.Direction: For the Prepare Gorgonzola and Egg Mixture
Separate the yolks from 4 organic eggs.
In a mixing bowl, combine the egg yolks with 3 oz of crumbly Gorgonzola, mashing up the Gorgonzola until thoroughly combined. Set aside.
For the Render Crispy Bacon:
Slice 3 slices of thick-cut black pepper bacon into batons (about ½ inch wide or less).
Place the bacon in a cold saucepan or saucier and turn on medium heat to render the fat.
Stir frequently and remove the bacon once it becomes crispy.
Take 1 tablespoon of the bacon fat and add it to the egg and Gorgonzola mixture while warm, tempering the eggs. Set aside.
For the Prepare Pasta:

Tip- If making a small portion of pasta be sure not to use too large of a pot of water.  You want a high concentration of starch in your pasta water, so if there is too much water, there will be a low concentration.  This starchy pasta water will get added to the sauce, so the higher the concentration of starch, the more it will thicken your sauce.  So use just enough water to boil your pasta.

A tip I learned from J. Kenji Lopez-Alt is to use a 12” skillet to boil your pasta water.  It allows you to use as little water as possible, so in the end, your pasta water is highly concentrated with starch.  It will then be extremely effective in thickening your pasta water.  While it is not necessary, it can make a big difference in your final product.
Bring a pot of water to a boil and add a generous pinch of salt.
Consider using a 12” skillet to boil water for a more concentrated starch content in the pasta water.
Add pasta to the boiling water and cook for 2 minutes less than the package directions recommend. Do not discard the pasta water.
For the Sauce:
In a separate pan, toast 1 teaspoon of freshly cracked black pepper.
Add 2 ladles of pasta water to the pan on high heat and bring it to a simmer.
Add 2 tablespoons of cold unsalted butter and mix to emulsify.
Once the pasta has cooked 2 minutes less than the package instructions, transfer it to the skillet with the pepper and butter emulsion.
Simmer in the skillet while tossing occasionally to aerate the "sauce." The pre-emulsified mixture coats the spaghetti.
Turn off the heat after the pasta is fully cooked in the skillet.
Let it cool for about 1 minute before adding the egg and Gorgonzola mixture.
Stir vigorously immediately to prevent the egg mixture from scrambling.
If the sauce is not saucy enough, add a splash of pasta water to achieve the desired consistency.
If there is too much liquid, turn the heat to MED-LOW and continue to toss and stir until the sauce thickens and coats the noodles.
For the Serve:
Serve immediately on a hot plate, garnished with extra Gorgonzola and crispy bacon bits.

Creator: rafifronzaglia
Name: Gorgonzola Pasta
Description:
I DID NOT expect this to blow up as much as it did on Instagram…  It’s currently my most viewed video on Instagram, and my 2nd most viewed video of all time!  Anyways, I had just gotten my brand new camera (Sony FX30), and this was actually the first video I filmed on it after spending the prior week learning how to use the camera.  Felt like getting creative and getting as many new shots/angles as possible, and it turned out pretty well for the video I guess, haha.
Anyways, the inspiration for this recipe came from a video I saw on tiktok.  I can’t remember exactly the name of the creator but it was a sausage, saffron, and gorgonzola pasta.  I just thought the idea of gorgonzola in pasta was so damn good that I had to make a version of it.  Landed on the idea of using gorgonzola in replacement of parmigiano or pecorino in a carbonara.  Then, when I was at the store looking for pancetta, I actually found some super high quality, thick cut, black pepper bacon.  I knew that’d be the perfect substitute for guanciale in this gorgonzola “carbonara”.  So anyways hope y’all enjoy this take on a gorgonzola “carbonara” where I utilize carbonara techniques, with gorgonzola and bacon.
